  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency and naturalness at the per-mutation step (it uses domain-specific, metamorphic transformations intended to preserve human-perceived meaning, and uses conservative transformation parameters so perturbations are slight). However, the coverage-guided testing procedure keeps mutants that remain valid as new seeds and mutates them further (they are added back into the test queue), and the paper does not describe any mechanism that bounds cumulative distortion relative to the original seed or otherwise prevents multi-step drift. Thus semantic/naturalness guarantees apply between successive mutation steps but the design does not control accumulated drift across iterations.",
  "evidence": "Page 482, Section 5.2 (Coverage-Guided Testing of RNNs): \"A mutant is an adversarial sample if it is predicted incorrectly by the network. Otherwise, if the mutant improves the coverage, it is then retained as an interesting seed and added back to the queue.\" (Algorithm 2 / explanatory text). \n\nPage 482, Section 5.2: \"For CGT, we mainly focus on image classification and apply the metamorphic mutation strategy [55] for generating new mutants that would keep the prediction meaning from the human’s perspective during testing.\" \n\nPage 483, Section 6.1 (Experiment Settings / Data Preparation): \"For both audio and image case, we set conservative parameters for transformation so that the perturbation on original samples is slight and imperceptible. Note that all the adversarial samples are also with minimal perturbations and not perceptible by human.\""
